In Unity, UI elements on a Canvas operate in a different coordinate space than standard 3D objects. Canvas elements use a 2D coordinate system for layout and positioning, which can be in pixels (for Screen Space - Overlay mode) or in meters (for World Space mode). To make the `InitHand` method work with Canvas coordinates, you'll need to adjust it based on the type of Canvas you're using. Here's a breakdown for each scenario:

### For Screen Space - Overlay Canvas:
You don't need to transform points since canvas positions match screen coordinates directly. Initialize the `_plane` to use the screen's forward direction.

```csharp
private void InitHand()
{
    // Screen Space Overlay mode uses screen coordinates.
    _a = curveStart;
    _b = transform.position;  // This should be a rectTransform's anchored position if you want it to match UI positioning.
    _c = curveEnd;

    // Ensure that the size and offsets here are computed in screen space (pixels).
    _handBounds = new Rect((handOffset - handSize / 2), handSize); 

    // Screen forward plane (Z-depth doesn't matter in screen space overlay)
    _plane = new Plane(Vector3.forward, Vector3.zero); 

    _prevMousePos = Input.mousePosition;
}
```

### For World Space Canvas:
UI elements in a World Space Canvas are placed in the world like regular 3D objects. Here's how you'd modify `InitHand` accordingly:

```csharp
private void InitHand()
{
    Canvas canvasComponent = GetComponentInParent<Canvas>();

    // If the hand is intended to be a UI element, transform the points taking into account the RectTransform.
    RectTransform rectTransform = GetComponent<RectTransform>();

    // Convert curveStart and curveEnd to world positions
    _a = rectTransform.TransformPoint(curveStart);
    _b = rectTransform.position;  // This would join the two sides of the bezier curve, assuming transform.position is central to the hand.
    _c = rectTransform.TransformPoint(curveEnd);

    // Hand bounds should be in local space (and thus size in meters not pixels)
    _handBounds = new Rect((handOffset - handSize / 2), handSize); 

    // The Canvas plane needs to be the plane of the RectTransform
    _plane = new Plane(rectTransform.forward, rectTransform.position);

    _prevMousePos = Input.mousePosition;
}
```

Modify the rest of your script to use `RectTransform` and methods like `RectTransformUtility.ScreenPointToWorldPointInRectangle` where required to convert between screen space and world space coordinates.

Additionally, keep in mind that input must be adjusted for UI elements if using `EventSystem` and `GraphicRaycaster` for UI interaction, often with raycasts using `PointerEventData`. This can replace some of the manual mouse position checks and collision detection logic with the built-in systems designed for UI elements in Unity.

The `updateHierarchyOrder` boolean flag in the `HandController` script is a custom flag likely used to determine whether or not the script should automatically update the hierarchy order (sibling index) of cards within the hand when they are rearranged.

In Unity, UI elements are rendered in the order of their hierarchy. This means that elements lower in the hierarchy are rendered on top of elements that are higher up. When dealing with a hand of cards in a game, it can be visually important for the cards to overlap correctly. For example, a card that is being actively selected or dragged should be rendered on top of the other cards.

When the `updateHierarchyOrder` is set to `true`, the script would be enabled to automatically manage the sibling index of each card's `Transform` in the hierarchy. Here's how it would be used in some methods:

**MoveCardToIndex:**
When a card is rearranged in the hand list (`hand`), it may also need to be moved in Unity's hierarchy order to reflect the new rendering order. This is achieved by setting the card's sibling index:

```csharp
if (updateHierarchyOrder)
{
    card.transform.SetSiblingIndex(toIndex);
}
```

**AddCardToHand:**
When adding a card to the hand, you might want to ensure it is also placed correctly in the hierarchy for rendering:

```csharp
if (updateHierarchyOrder)
{
    card.transform.SetParent(transform);
    card.transform.SetSiblingIndex(index);
}
```

**RemoveCardFromHand:**
When removing a card, similarly, you could change its hierarchy order so that it doesn't affect the rendering order of the remaining cards:

```csharp
if (updateHierarchyOrder)
{
    CardBase card = hand[index];
    card.transform.SetParent(transform.parent);
    card.transform.SetSiblingIndex(transform.GetSiblingIndex() + 1);
}
```

By updating the hierarchy order when cards are added, moved, or removed from the hand, the visual presentation of layered cards can be maintained accurately throughout gameplay.

It's worth noting that, depending on the game's design, you may not always want to update the hierarchy order every time cards are manipulated. For instance, you may have a different system that controls the rendering order or animations. In such cases, you can set `updateHierarchyOrder` to `false` to prevent the script from automatically changing the hierarchy.

