It's common to get the references for UI elements through the Unity Editor by dragging and dropping the UI GameObject into a reference field on a script component. This avoids needing to call `GetComponent` which can be less efficient if done repeatedly.

When working with UI elements, always remember that you should use `RectTransform` instead of `Transform`, as the UI elements are laid out in a 2D space and have additional properties and methods which are not present in the standard `Transform` component.

To convert RectTransform coordinates to world coordinates, you can use the `TransformPoint` method provided by the RectTransform component. This method translates a position from local space to world space, which is useful when you want to know the actual position of a UI element in the scene.

Here’s an example of how you can do this conversion:
```csharp
// Get a reference to the RectTransform component
RectTransform rectTransform = myCanvasElement.GetComponent<RectTransform>();

// If you want to convert the center point of the RectTransform to world space
Vector3 worldPosition = rectTransform.TransformPoint(rectTransform.rect.center);

// If you want to convert one of the corners to world space
Vector3 worldPositionBottomLeft = rectTransform.TransformPoint(rectTransform.rect.min);
Vector3 worldPositionTopRight = rectTransform.TransformPoint(rectTransform.rect.max);
```

The `rect` property of the RectTransform gives you the rectangle which defines the UI element’s size and position within its parent, while `min` and `max` are shorthand for the bottom left and top right corners, respectively.

Keep in mind that the `TransformPoint` method assumes that the point you provide is relative to the RectTransform's local space. If you are working with a Canvas in World Space, its UI elements' world positions correspond directly to their RectTransform positions. If you're dealing with a Screen Space Canvas, and you want to get a world position (for example, to place a 3D object where a UI element is), you'd need to use methods like `RectTransformUtility.ScreenPointToWorldPointInRectangle`, passing the correct camera for screen space canvases. 

